</ref>\n\nOn November 29, 2016, it was announced that Price would be nominated for [[United States Secretary of Health and Human Services|Secretary of Health and Human Services]] by [[President-elect of the United States|President-elect]] [[Donald Trump]] when he takes office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/11/28/trump-picks-congressman-tom-price-as-health-and-human-services-secretary/|title=Trump picks Congressman Tom Price as health and human services secretary|website=Washington Post|access-date=2016-11-29}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and medical career==\nPrice was born in the [[Michigan]] capital, [[Lansing]]. He grew up in [[Dearborn, Michigan|Dearborn]], where he attended Adams Jr. High and [[Dearborn High School]].\n\nHe graduated with an [[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]] degree from the [[University of Michigan Health System]]. He completed his residency at [[Emory University]] in Atlanta, and decided to settle in the suburb of [[Roswell, Georgia|Roswell]], where he still lives. He is a past President of the Roswell [[Rotary Club]] and has served on the Boards of the North Fulton [[Chamber of Commerce]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Arena Rep. Tom Price|url=http://www.politico.com/arena/bio/rep_tom_price.html|website=Politico The Arena|accessdate=November 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe ran an orthopedic clinic in Atlanta for 20 years before returning to Emory as assistant professor of orthopedic surgery. Price also was the director of the orthopedic clinic at Atlanta's [[Grady Memorial Hospital]].\n\nPrice is a member of the [[Association of American Physicians and Surgeons]], a politically conservative non-profit association founded in 1943 to \"fight socialized medicine and to fight the government takeover of medicine.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.esquire.com/news-politics/politics/news/a38354/surprise-new-house-majority-leader-crazy/|title=The GOP's Search for a New House Majority Leader Is a Race to the Bottom|last=Pierce|first=Charles P.|date=September 29, 2015|work=Esquire|access-date=December 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/19/business/19physicians.html\n|title=Vocal Physicians Group Renews Health Law Fight|last=Meier|first=Barry|date=January 18, 2011|access-date=December 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Georgia Senate (1996\u20132005)==\n\n===Elections===\nIn 1996, State Senator Sallie Newbill (R) decided not to run for re-election. Price was the Republican nominee for Georgia's 56th senate district. In the November general election, he defeated Democrat Ellen Milholland 71%\u201329%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=288507|title=GA State Senate 56 Race - Nov 05, 1996|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref> In 1998, he won re-election to a second term by defeating her in a rematch, 75%\u201325%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=288618|title=GA State Senate 56 Race - Nov 03, 1998|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref> In 2000 and 2002, he won re-election to a third and fourth term unopposed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=288768|title= GA State Senate 056 Race - Nov 07, 2000|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=288780|title= GA State Senate 056 Race - Nov 05, 2002|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* Administrative Affairs\n* Appropriations\n* Economic Development and Tourism (Vice Chair)\n* Education<ref>{{cite news| url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MT&s_site=macon&p_multi=MT&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB76C5057FB4B93&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Barnes' Bill Close to Passing Committee |newspaper=Macon Telegraph| date=February 19, 2000}}</ref>\n* Ethics\n* Insurance and Labor\n* Health and Human Services\n* Reapportionment\n* Reapportionment and Redistricting (Chair)\n* Rules (Secretary)\n* Veterans and Consumer Affairs<ref name=\"senate.ga.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://www.senate.ga.gov/senators/en-US/member.aspx?Member=329&Session=1|title=Georgia State Senator Tom Price (Republican - 56)|publisher=Georgia State Senate}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives (2005\u2013present)==\n\n===Elections===\n[[File:Tom Price original.jpg|thumb|left|100px|Price in 2005]]\n;2004\nIn 2004, U.S. Congressman [[Johnny Isakson]] of [[Georgia's 6th congressional district]] decided not to run for re-election in order to run for the U.S. Senate. No [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] even filed, meaning that whoever won the Republican primary would be virtually assured of being the district's next congressman. The 6th district was so heavily Republican that any Democratic candidate would have faced nearly impossible odds in any event. Six other Republican candidates filed to run, most notably state senators Robert Lamutt and Chuck Clay. Price was the only major candidate from [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton County]], while Lamutt and Clay were both from [[Cobb County]]. On July 20, 2004, Price ranked first with 35% of the vote, but failed to reach the 50% threshold needed to win the Republican nomination. Lamutt qualified for the run-off, ranking second with 28% of the vote. Price won two of the district's three counties: [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton]] with 63% and [[Cherokee County, Georgia|Cherokee]] with 35%. Lamutt carried [[Cobb County, Georgia|Cobb]] with 31% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=4653|title= GA - District 06 - R Primary Race - Jul 20, 2004|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref> In the August 10 run-off election, Price defeated Lamutt 54%\u201346%. They split the vote in Cherokee, but Price carried Fulton by a landslide of 79% of the vote. Lamutt couldn't eliminate that deficit as he won Cobb with just 59% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=114737|title=GA District 06 - R Runoff Race - Aug 10, 2004|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref> Price won the general election unopposed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=4101|title= GA - District 06 Race - Nov 02, 2004|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n;2006\nIn 2006, Price drew one primary challenger, John Konop, whom he easily defeated 82%\u201318%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=311132|title=GA District 06- R Primary Race - Jul 18, 2006|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref> In November, he won re-election to a second term with 72% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=206831|title=GA - District 06 Race - Nov 07, 2006|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n;2008\u20132014\nPrice won re-election in 2008 (68%),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=387947|title=GA - District 06 Race - Nov 04, 2008|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref> 2010 (99.9%),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=488686|title=GA - District 06 Race - Nov 02, 2010|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref> and 2012 (65%).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=753473|title=GA District 06 Race - Nov 06, 2012|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n;2016\nPrice won the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Georgia, 2016|election in 2016]] against Rodney Stooksbury (Democratic). Price received 61.6% of the votes.\n\n===Tenure===\n[[File:U.S. Congressman Tom Price speaking at the 2010 Conservative Political Action Conference (CPAC).jpg|thumb|Congressman Price speaking at the 2010 [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC)]]\n[[File:U.S. Congressman Tom Price speaking at Freedomworks New Fair Deal Rally outside the US Capitol.jpg|thumb|Congressman Price speaking at Freedomworks New Fair Deal Rally outside the [[US Capitol]]]]\nIn 2011, Price voted to prohibit federal funding of [[NPR|National Public Radio]],<ref name=\"govtrack.us 174\">{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h2011-190 |title= House Vote On Passage: H. Res. 174: Providing for consideration of the bill (H.R. 1076) to |publisher=GovTrack |date=March 17, 2011 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref> to terminate the Emergency Mortgage Relief Program,<ref name=\"govtrack.us 836\">{{cite web |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h2011-174 |title=GovTrack: House Vote On Passage: H.R. 836: Emergency Mortgage Relief Program Termination Act |publisher=Govtrack.us |date=March 11, 2011 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref> to extend the [[Patriot Act]],<ref name=\"govtrack.us 514\">{{cite web |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h2011-26 |title=GovTrack: House Vote On Passage: H.R. 514: FISA Sunsets Extension Act of 2011 |publisher=Govtrack.us |date=February 8, 2011 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"govtrack.us 79\">{{cite web |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h2011-29 |title=GovTrack: House Vote On Passage: H. Res. 79: Providing for consideration of the bill (H.R. 514) to extend |publisher=Govtrack.us |date=February 10, 2011 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref> to repeal portions of the Health Care and Education Reconciliation Act of 2010 on multiple occasions,<ref>http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2011/roll009.xml</ref><ref>http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2011/roll010.xml</ref> to reduce non-security discretionary spending to 2008 levels<ref>http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2011/roll017.xml</ref><ref name=\"govtrack.us 43\">{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h2011-18 |title=GovTrack: House Vote On Passage: H. Res. 43: Providing for consideration of the resolution (H. Res. 38) |publisher=Govtrack.us |date=January 24, 2011 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"govtrack.us 38\">{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h2011-20 |title=GovTrack: House Vote On Passage: H. Res. 38: Reducing non-security spending to fiscal year 2008 levels or |publisher=Govtrack.us |date=January 25, 2011 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref> (and subsequently voted against several amendments offered via motions to recommit with instructions),<ref name=\"govtrack.us 19\">{{cite web |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h2011-19 |title=GovTrack: House Vote No. 19 (Jan 25, 2011) |publisher=Govtrack.us |date=January 25, 2011 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref> to reduce federal spending and the deficit by terminating taxpayer financing of presidential election campaigns and party conventions,<ref name=\"govtrack.us 22\">{{cite web |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h2011-22 |title=GovTrack: House Vote No. 22 (Jan 26, 2011) |publisher=Govtrack.us |date=January 26, 2011 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref> to provide funding for government agencies, including the Department of Defense, through September 30, 2011,<ref name=\"govtrack.us 92\">{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h2011-39 |title=GovTrack: House Vote On Passage: H. Res. 92: Providing for consideration of the bill (H.R. 1) making |publisher=Govtrack.us |date=February 15, 2011 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref> to cut the Federal Housing Authority's refinancing program,<ref name=\"govtrack.us 150\">{{cite web |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h2011-166 |title=GovTrack: House Vote On Passage: H. Res. 150: Providing for consideration of the bill (H.R. 830) to |publisher=Govtrack.us |date=March 9, 2011 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref> and against a resolution which would force the president to withdraw American forces from Iraq.<ref name=\"govtrack.us 28\">{{cite web |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h2011-193 |title=GovTrack: House Vote On Passage: H. Con. Res. 28: Directing the President, pursuant to section 5(c) of |publisher=Govtrack.us |date=March 17, 2011 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref> In 2013, he was the main sponsor of the Require a PLAN Act (mandating that the President identify a fiscal year in the budget will be balanced).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hr444|title=Require a PLAN Act (2013 - H.R. 444)|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=GovTrack.us>{{cite web |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hr444 |publisher=GovTrack.us|title=H.R. 444 (113th): Require a PLAN Act|accessdate=April 6, 2013}}</ref> He voted for the [[No Budget, No Pay Act]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hr325|title=No Budget, No Pay Act of 2013 (2013 - H.R. 325)|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"GovTrack.us 30\">{{cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/113-2013/s11|publisher=GovTrack.us|title=H.R. 325 (113th): No Budget, No Pay Act of 2013|accessdate=April 6, 2013}}</ref> and a resolution establishing a budget for the United States Government for FY 2014 that passed the House of Representatives.<ref name=\"GovTrack.us 25\">{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hconres25 |title=H.Con.Res. 25 (113th): Establishing the budget for the United States Government for fiscal year 2014 and setting forth appropriate budgetary levels for fiscal years 2015 through 2023.|publisher=GovTrack.us |accessdate=April 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\nPrice opposes abortion and supported the proposed Protect Life Act of 2011, which would have denied [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] (PPACA) funding to health care plans that offered abortion (the PPACA already prevented public funding covering abortions) and allowed hospitals to decline to provide abortions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/10/13/protect-life-act-passes-house-of-representatives_n_1009876.html|title=House Passes Controversial Anti-Abortion Bill|first=Laura|last=Bassett|date=October 13, 2011|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/public-statement/643441/price-statement-on-the-protect-life-act/?search=abortion|title=Price Statement on the Protect Life Act|publisher=Vote Smart|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref> The bill excludes cases where the pregnancy is the result of rape or incest and in cases where a woman suffers from a medical issue that would place her at risk of death unless an abortion is performed.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Greenberg|first1=Julia|title=House Passes \u2018Protect Life Act,\u2019 Controversial Anti-Abortion Funding Bill|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/house-passes-protect-life-act-controversial-anti-abortion-funding-bill-video-323317|accessdate=27 December 2016|publisher=International Business Times|date=October 13, 2011}}</ref> He was rated at 100 by the National Right to Life Center. He was rated at 0 by Planned Parenthood and [[NARAL Pro-Choice America]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/11853/tom-price/2|title=Tom Price's Ratings and Endorsements on Issue: Abortion|publisher=Vote Smart|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"thehill.com\">[http://thehill.com/resources/lawmaker-ratings/82817-rep-tom-price-r-ga%2520]{{dead link|date=November 2016}}</ref> He participated in the 2011 [[March for Life (Washington, D.C.)|March for Life]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/public-statement/582186/price-statement-on-march-for-life/?search=abortion|title=Price Statement on March for Life|publisher=Vote Smart|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPrice opposes [[gun control]]. He praised the Supreme Court's decisions in ''[[District of Columbia v. Heller]]'', which found that the absolute prohibition of handguns in the [[District of Columbia]] was unconstitutional, and ''[[McDonald v. Chicago]]'', which stated that the [[Second Amendment to the United States Constitution|Second Amendment]] applied to the states.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/public-statement/529093/supreme-court-reaffirms-second-amendment-rights/?search=second%20amendment|title=Supreme Court Reaffirms Second Amendment Rights|publisher=Vote Smart|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref> He was given an \"A\" grade by the National Rifle Association Political Victory Fund, a 92% approval rating overall from the [[National Rifle Association]] and an 83% approval rating<ref name=\"Project Vote Smart\">{{cite web|title=2012 Ratings on Gun Rights \u2013 Elected to 113th Congress|url=http://votesmart.org/interest-group/1226/rating/6577#.UWBwZc2FYfw|publisher=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=April 6, 2013}}</ref> from the [[Gun Owners of America]], and a 0% approval rating from the Brady Campaign to Prevent Gun Violence.<ref name=\"thehill.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/11853/tom-price/37|title=Tom Price's Ratings and Endorsements on Issue: Guns|publisher=Vote Smart|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPrice voted against a bill prohibiting job discrimination based on sexual orientation (Nov 2007). He voted in favor of constitutionally defining marriage as one-man-one-woman (Jul 2006). Representative Price voted against H.R. 2965, which would have ended [[Don't ask, don't tell]]. He receives a 0% rating by the [[Human Rights Campaign]], a gay rights organization.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/GA/Tom_Price.htm|title=Tom Price on the Issues|first=|last=OnTheIssues.org|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nPrice does not support federal regulation of farming. He has voted against regulating and restricting farmers, earning him a 70% from the [[American Farm Bureau Federation]]. However, due to this belief, the [[National Farmers Union (United States)|National Farmers Union]] gave him a 0% approval rate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/11853/tom-price/4|title=Tom Price's Ratings and Endorsements on Issue: Agriculture and Food|publisher=Vote Smart|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref> He supported the Farm Dust Regulation Prevention Act, stating that it would keep the [[Environmental Protection Agency]] from applying too many regulations to farming and ranching.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/public-statement/656161/price-statement-on-house-passage-of-farm-dust-regulation-prevention-act/?search=farmers|title=Price Statement on House Passage of Farm Dust Regulation Prevention Act|publisher=Vote Smart|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref> He also voted for the Agricultural Disaster Assistance Act of 2012 which, had it become law, would have made supplemental agricultural disaster assistance available, if needed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/112/hr6233|title=Agricultural Disaster Assistance Act of 2012 (2012 - H.R. 6233)|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/bill/votes/41290|title=HR 6233 - Agricultural Disaster Assistance Act of 2012 - Voting Record|publisher=Vote Smart|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 Price signed a pledge sponsored by [[Americans for Prosperity]] promising to vote against any global warming legislation that would raise taxes.<ref>http://americansforprosperity.org/noclimatetax//wp-content/uploads/2008/08/price.pdf</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\n[[File:Tom Price by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg|left|thumb|Price speaking on a panel about healthcare at the 2014 Conservative Political Action Conference]]\nPrice is the sponsor of the [[Empowering Patients First Act]] (EPFA), which he first introduced in the 111th Congress and has reintroduced in each Congress since then. Originally intended to be a Republican alternative to Democratic efforts to reform the health care system, it has since been positioned by Price and other Republicans as a potential replacement to the PPACA. The bill, among other things, creates and expands tax credits for purchasing health insurance, allows for some interstate health insurance markets, and reforms medical malpractice lawsuits.\n\nPrice introduced the [[Pro-Growth Budgeting Act of 2013 (H.R. 1874; 113th Congress)]] on May 8, 2013.<ref name=1874sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 1874 \u2013 Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/1874|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=March 28, 2014}}</ref> The bill would require the [[Congressional Budget Office]] to provide a macroeconomic impact analysis for bills that are estimated to have a large budgetary effect.<ref name=1874cbo>{{cite web|title=H.R. 1874 \u2013 CBO|url=http://cbo.gov/publication/45213|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=March 28, 2014}}</ref> Price said it was necessary because of the Congressional Budget Office's current method of reviewing bills just to see what they would cost. Price said \"that is a model that has proven to be incapable of providing the type of macroeconomic diagnosis folks need to make sure we are pursuing policies that will help generate economic opportunity and bring down the nation's debt.\"<ref name=Housepushbudget>{{cite news|last=Kasperowicz|first=Pete|title=House to push budget reforms next week|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/economics-trade/202010-house-to-push-budget-reforms-next-week|accessdate=April 1, 2014|newspaper=The Hill|date=March 28, 2014}}</ref> H.R. 1874 has passed the House but has yet to become law.\n\nIn total, Price has sponsored 55 bills, including:<ref>{{cite web|title=Representative Price's Legislation|url=http://www.congress.gov/member/tom-price/1778?q=%7B%22search%22%3A%5B%22Price%22%5D%2C%22sponsorship%22%3A%22sponsored%22%2C%22type%22%3A%22bills%22%7D|publisher=Library of Congress|accessdate=December 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====109th Congress (2005\u20132006)====\n* H.R. 3693, a bill to prevent all illegal border crossings after a certain date, introduced September 7, 2005\n* H.R. 3860, a bill to require each state and U.S. territory to maintain a [[Sex offender registries in the United States|sex offender registry]], to increase punishments for sexual and violent crimes against children and minors, and to require background checks of individuals before approval of adoptive or foster services, introduced September 22, 2005\n* H.R. 3941, a bill to reduce foreign oil consumption to less than 25% of total oil consumption by no later than 2015, introduced September 29, 2005, reintroduced in the 110th Congress as H.R. 817\n* H.R. 6133, a bill to create national standards for work in laboratories that includes requiring proficiency in [[cytology]] or the study of cells, introduced September 21, 2006. H.R. 6133's companion bill was S. 4056.\n\n====110th Congress (2007\u20132008)====\n* H.R. 1685, a bill to require holders of personal financial data to increase security of such data, introduced March 26, 2007\n* H.R. 1761, a bill to create a competitive grant program to reward such grants to educational institutions and systems to develop and implement performance-based compensation systems for teachers to encourage teachers to improve educational outcomes, introduced March 29, 2007, reintroduced in the 111th Congress as H.R. 3683\n* H.R. 2626, a bill to allow for tax credits and deductions for purchasing health insurance, to revise government employer contribution amounts, to reform malpractice lawsuits, to provide financial aid to introduce [[health information technology]], to allow for a tax credit for emergency room physicians to offset costs incurred because of the [[Emergency Medical Treatment and Active Labor Act]], and to promote interstate health insurance markets, introduced June 7, 2007. This bill served as the precursor to EPFA, and most of H.R. 2626's provisions are included in EPFA.\n* H.R. 4464, a bill to amend the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]] to clarify that it is not unlawful for any employer to require proficiency in English as a condition of employment, introduced December 12, 2007, reintroduced in the 111th Congress as H.R. 1588\n* H.R. 6910, a bill to expand oil and natural gas drilling and use revenue generated from such drilling to fund monetary rewards for advancing the research, development, demonstration, and commercial application of alternative fuel vehicles, introduced September 18, 2008\n\n====111th Congress (2009\u20132010)====\n* H.R. 464, a bill to require states to cover 90% of eligible children for the [[State Children's Health Insurance Program]] (SCHIP) in the program for households with incomes below 200% of the federal poverty level (FPL), with special rules above 200% of the FPL, to prohibit SCHIP from funding child health care for children in households above 250% of the FPL, and to require more than one health plan to be offered in SCHIP, introduced January 13, 2009. Modified versions of this bill's provisions make up [[Empowering Patients First Act#Title IV \u2013 Safety Net Reforms|Title IV of EPFA]].\n* H.R. 3140, a bill to repeal all unpaid provisions of the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009]], to terminate the [[Troubled Asset Relief Program]] (TARP), and to allocate TARP repayments to reducing the federal government's public debt, introduced July 9, 2009\n* H.R. 3372, a bill to develop best practice guidelines for treating medical conditions and to reform malpractice lawsuits, introduced July 29, 2009, reintroduced in the 112th Congress as H.R. 2363. Modified versions of this bill's provisions make up [[Empowering Patients First Act#Title V \u2013 Lawsuit Abuse Reforms|Title V of EPFA]].\n* H.R. 6170, a bill to prevent the Secretary of Health and Human Services from precluding an enrollee, participant, or beneficiary in a health benefits plan from entering into any contract or arrangement for health care with any health care provider, excluding [[Medicaid]] and [[TRICARE]], introduced September 22, 2010. This bill's provisions are included in [[Empowering Patients First Act#Title X \u2013 Patient Freedom of Choice|Title X of EPFA]].\n* H.R. 6171, a bill to prevent the Secretary of Health and Human Services or any state from requiring any health care provider to participate in any health plan as a condition of licensure of the provider in any state, introduced September 22, 2010, reintroduced in the 112th and 113th Congresses as H.R. 969. This bill's provisions are included in [[Empowering Patients First Act#Title X \u2013 Patient Freedom of Choice|Title X of EPFA]].\n\n====112th Congress (2011\u20132012)====\n* H.R. 1700, a bill to allow for Medicare beneficiaries to contract with any health care professionals that provide care covered under the Medicare program, with special circumstances, introduced March 3, 2011, reintroduced in the 113th Congress as H.R. 1310. This bill's provisions are included in [[Empowering Patients First Act#Title X \u2013 Patient Freedom of Choice|Title X of EPFA]].\n* H.R. 2077, a bill to repeal the medical [[loss ratio]] provision of the PPACA, introduced June 1, 2011\n* H.R. 4066, a bill to exclude [[pathologist]]s from Medicare and Medicaid incentive payments and penalties relating to electronic health records, introduced February 6, 2012, reintroduced in the 113th Congress as H.R. 1309\n* H.R. 6616, a bill to exempt U.S. [[Security (finance)|securities]] transactions from financial taxes and penalties imposed by other nations, introduced November 19, 2012, reintroduced in the 113th Congress as H.R. 2546\n\n====113th Congress (2013\u20132014)====\n* H.R. 1990 and H.R. 2009, bills to prohibit the Secretary of the Treasury, or any delegate of the Secretary, from implementing or enforcing any provisions of or amendments made by the PPACA or the [[Health Care and Education Reconciliation Act of 2010]], introduced May 15 and 16, 2013. H.R. 2009 has passed the House but has yet to become law.\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on the Budget|Committee on the Budget]]'''\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|Committee on Ways and Means]]'''\n** [[United States House Ways and Means Subcommittee on Health|Subcommittee on Health]]\n** [[United States House Ways and Means Subcommittee on Human Resources|Subcommittee on Human Resources]]\n\n==Personal life==\nPrice and his wife Betty reside in Roswell, and have one child, Robert Price.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tomprice.house.gov/about/full-biography |title=Tom Price Bio |accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref> Betty served on the Roswell City Council and was elected to the [[Georgia House of Representatives]] in a 2015 special election to succeed the late [[Harry Geisinger]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.neighbornewspapers.com/view/full_story/26753475/article-Price-wins-District-48-election?instance=all |title=Price wins District 48 election |author=Katherine Frye |publisher=Neighborhood Newspapers |date=July 14, 2015}}</ref> Price is a [[Presbyterian]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* [[Physicians' Council for Responsible Reform]]\n* [[Physicians in the United States Congress]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline|Tom Price}}\n* [http://www.house.gov/tomprice/ Congressman Tom Price] official House site\n* [http://www.tomprice.com/ Tom Price for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Georgia/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Tom_Price_%5BR-6%5D|Tom Price}}\n* {{C-SPAN|Tom Price}}\n{{CongLinks | congbio = p000591 | ballot = Tom_Price | nndb = 302/000087041 | votesmart = 11853 | govtrack = 400626 | natjournal = 402 | opencong = 400626 | rollcall = 20268 | factcheck = tom-price | politifact = tom-price | fec = H4GA06087 | opensecrets = N00026160 | assets = tom-price | legistorm = 430/Rep_Thomas_E_Price.html | followthemoney = 18267 | ontheissues = GA/Tom_Price.htm | congress = tom-price/1778 | worldcat = lccn-nb2002-653